    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "e11fbfa8cda4b4052942b875b59962b6d3d94529907d57dab1e6afc5898bbd38",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "Erd\\H{o}s noted that the greedy algorithm showed $f(n)\\geq \\lfloor \\log_3 n\\rfloor$."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "c88e897e5b39929cf907d11d080f24d13ce76d52f0ff5b19a31bd440afa1320e",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Let $f(n)$ be the maximal $k$ such that in any set $A\\subset \\mathbb{R}$ of size $n$ there is a subset $B\\subseteq A$ of size $\\lvert B\\rvert\\geq k$ which is dissociated that is, the sums $\\sum_{b\\in S}b$ are distinct for all $S\\subseteq B$. Estimate $f(n)$ - in particular, is it true that\\[f(n)\\geq \\lfloor \\log_2 n\\rfloor?\\]"
    }
  },
